<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=7214&amp;p=70967#p70967</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=7214&amp;p=70967#p70967"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Convince me that making NES games is a good idea.]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=7214&amp;p=70967#p70967"><![CDATA[
I'm not sure how much planning is the healthy amount to make before coding. When I was younger, I wanted to see results fast, so I'd draw a shitload of sprites first and then make sure they were displayed on the screen as soon as possible. Note that I'm not even talking about the NES here, this was when I made games in QBasic. That approach did show results quickly, but eventually I couldn't get the program to evolve because of poor planning of the underlying architecture, so I would eventually give up on these projects.<br /><br />Nowadays, I plan a lot before anything else, and I don't start coding until I have at least 60% of the game aspects figured out (which means a lot of schematics, pseudo-code, and things like that). However, because of all the time I spend planning and implementing this basic architecture, it takes me a long time to see something actually move on the screen, so there isn't much motivation to go forward.<br /><br />If I ever find what the perfect balance is, I'll be sure to tell you guys! =)<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=95">tokumaru</a> — Fri Dec 03, 2010 12:53 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
